"Redner S., Petersen M.R.","Role of global warming on the statistics of record-breaking temperatures",2006,"Physical Review E - Statistical, Nonlinear, and Soft Matter Physics","74","6", 061114,"","",,,10.1103/PhysRevE.74.061114,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845732195&partnerID=40&md5=240cac9f009ef2bcaa0f3e65e10fc349","Center for Polymer Studies, Department of Physics, Boston University, Boston, MA 02215, United States; Computer and Computational Sciences Division, Center for Nonlinear Studies, Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM 87545, United States","Redner, S., Center for Polymer Studies, Department of Physics, Boston University, Boston, MA 02215, United States; Petersen, M.R., Computer and Computational Sciences Division, Center for Nonlinear Studies, Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM 87545, United States","We theoretically study the statistics of record-breaking daily temperatures and validate these predictions using both Monte Carlo simulations and 126 years of available data from the city of Philadelphia. Using extreme statistics, we derive the number and the magnitude of record temperature events, based on the observed Gaussian daily temperature distribution in Philadelphia, as a function of the number of years of observation. We then consider the case of global warming, where the mean temperature systematically increases with time. Over the 126-year time range of observations, we argue that the current warming rate is insufficient to measurably influence the frequency of record temperature events, a conclusion that is supported by numerical simulations and by the Philadelphia data. We also study the role of correlations between temperatures on successive days and find that they do not affect the frequency or magnitude of record temperature events. © 2006 The American Physical Society.",,"Computer simulation; Monte Carlo methods; Statistical mechanics; Temperature distribution; Temperature measurement; Gaussian daily temperature distribution; Temperature events; Global warming",,,,,,"Roach, J., (2005) Nat. Geogra. News, , http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2005/08/0816_050816_heat_wave. html, 16 August; Yan, Z., Jones, P.D., Davies, T.D., Moberg, A., Bergstroem, H., (2002) Clim. Change, 53, p. 355. , CLCHDX 0165-0009; Mearns, L.O., Katz, R.W., Schneider, S.H., (1984) J. Clim. Appl. Meteorol., 23, p. 1601. , JCAMEJ 0733-3021; Hansen, J., Fung, I., Lacis, A., Rind, D., Lebedeff, S., Ruedy, R., Russel, G., Stone, P., (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93, p. 9341. , JGREA2 0148-0227; Katz, R., Brown, B., (1992) Clim. Change, 21, p. 289. , CLCHDX 0165-0009; Colombo, A.F., Etkin, D., Karney, B.W., (1999) J. Clim., 12, p. 2490. , JLCLEL 0894-8755; Unkaévić, M., Vujović, D., Toi, C.I., (2005) Theor. Appl. Climatol., 82, p. 199. , TACLEK 0177-798X; Meehl, G., Karl, T., Easterling, D., Changnon, S., (2000) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 81, p. 413. , BAMIAT 0003-0007; (2001) IPCC, 2001: Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, , Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, edited by J. T. Houghton, Y. Ding, D. J. Griggs, M. Noguer, P. J. van der Linden, X. Dai, K. Maskell, and C. A. Johnson (Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, England; http://www.ems.psu.edu/PA_Climatologist/philadelphia/phlcomp.htmlVon Storch, H., Zwiers, F.W., (1999) Statistical Analysis in Climate Research, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, England; Reitan, C.H., Moran, J.M., (1977) Mon. Weather Rev., 105, p. 1442. , MWREAB 0027-0644; Balling Jr., R.C., Skindlov, J.A., Phillips, D.H., (1990) J. Clim., 3, p. 1491. , JLCLEL 0894-8755; Arnold, B.C., Balakrishnan, N., Nagaraja, H.N., (1998) Records, , John Wiley & Sons, New York; Godfrey, C.M., Wiliks, D.S., Schultz, D.M., (2002) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 83, p. 53. , BAMIAT 0003-0007; Vanmarcke, E., (1983) Random Fields: Analysis and Synthesis, , MIT Press, Cambridge, MA; Rice, S.O., (1944) Bell